    "infrastructure": ["Kubernetes", "Docker (distroless/Alpine hardened)", "BuildKit --secret mounts", "dumb-init", "HashiCorp Vault", "GitHub Actions"]
  },
  "key_decisions": [
    {
      "title": "Strangler-Fig Migration over Full Rewrite",
      "choice": "Incremental strangler-fig pattern with allowJs + checkJs TypeScript adoption first, then module-by-module conversion",
      "rationale": "A full rewrite would require freezing feature development, introduce a lengthy parallel-run period, and risk reintroducing the same security gaps under time pressure. Because the service is already an isolated microservice with defined API boundaries, strangler-fig allows each high-risk module — auth middleware, JWT handling, Mongoose models — to be hardened and converted independently, with regression tests validating contracts at each step. Big-bang rewrites in security-critical paths are rejected due to the blast radius of a botched migration."
    },
    {
      "title": "HashiCorp Vault Sidecar over Environment Variables or K8s Secrets Alone",
      "choice": "Vault agent sidecar injecting secrets to tmpfs-mounted files at pod startup, with BuildKit --secret mounts for build-time NPM auth",
      "rationale": "Plain environment variables are the root cause of the current credential leakage — they persist in Docker layer history and appear in CI logs. Kubernetes Secrets alone are base64-encoded and accessible to anyone with cluster read permissions, making them insufficient for NPM auth tokens and LDAP bind credentials. Vault provides dynamic secrets, audit logging, automatic rotation, and fine-grained policies. BuildKit --secret mounts ensure NPM_BASIC_AUTH is consumed during build and never written to any image layer, directly eliminating the CVE vector identified in the current Dockerfile."
    },
    {
      "title": "jsonwebtoken 9.x with Mandatory Algorithm Pinning over Alternative JWT Libraries",
      "choice": "Upgrade to jsonwebtoken 9.x with explicit algorithms array in all verify() calls",
      "rationale": "CVE-2022-23529 and CVE-2022-23539 in jsonwebtoken 8.x allow attackers to bypass verification via algorithm confusion attacks (e.g., RS256 key used as HS256 secret). jose and fast-jwt are credible alternatives, but switching libraries entirely would require auditing every verification call site and updating all JWT consumer contracts across Opsera internal libraries — a broader change than the security timeline permits. jsonwebtoken 9.x directly patches the CVEs, the API is backward-compatible with algorithm enforcement added, and the team's existing familiarity reduces migration risk. Algorithm pinning is enforced as a lint rule via ESLint custom rule."
    },
    {
      "title": "Remove PM2 — Single-Process Container Model with dumb-init",
      "choice": "Node.js as direct container entrypoint via dumb-init for proper PID 1 signal handling",
      "rationale": "PM2 was designed for bare-metal multi-process management on long-lived VMs. Inside a Kubernetes pod, it creates two layers of process supervision that conflict: PM2 intercepts SIGTERM before Kubernetes can gracefully drain the pod, restart logic fights with K8s liveness probes, and cluster mode inside a single-container pod wastes resources better allocated via pod horizontal scaling. dumb-init provides the only thing PM2 added value for in containers — correct PID 1 signal forwarding — without the conflicts. /healthz and /readyz endpoints replace PM2's health monitoring, integrating natively with K8s probe semantics."
    },
    {
      "title": "npm ci with Exact Version Pinning over npm install with Range Specifiers",
      "choice": "All internal Opsera packages pinned to exact versions (1.2.3), package-lock.json committed, npm ci enforced in all CI and Docker steps",
      "rationale": "The current 'latest' pinning of internal packages means any publish to the internal NPM registry can silently break production builds — a category of incident that is invisible until deployment. npm install resolves ranges at build time, making Docker image contents non-reproducible. npm ci consumes package-lock.json exactly, ensuring every build — developer laptop, CI, Docker — produces an identical dependency graph. A CI gate failing on package-lock.json drift prevents the common failure mode where a developer runs npm install locally and the lockfile diverges without review. This directly addresses the non-deterministic build problem identified as a core pain point."
    },
    {
      "title": "Redis 4.x with TLS over Unencrypted Redis 3.x",
      "choice": "redis@4.x client with mandatory TLS and certificate validation, rejecting plaintext connections",
      "rationale": "Redis 3.x is end-of-life with no upstream security patches. More critically, the current unencrypted Redis connection exposes analytics data in transit on internal Kubernetes network segments — a significant risk in multi-tenant or shared-cluster environments where network policies may be imperfect. redis@4.x introduces a completely redesigned async/await API (eliminating callback hell), first-class TypeScript support, and TLS as a first-class configuration option. Dragonfly and KeyDB were evaluated as Redis-compatible alternatives but rejected in favor of operational simplicity — redis@4.x drops in as a client replacement with well-understood Mongoose/Express integration patterns."
    },
    {
      "title": "date-fns over moment.js",
      "choice": "Replace moment.js with date-fns for all date manipulation",
      "rationale": "moment.js is officially in maintenance-only mode — the maintainers themselves recommend migrating. It is mutable (a source of subtle bugs), not tree-shakeable (adding unnecessary bundle weight to an analytics API that should be lean), and has no TypeScript-first design. date-fns is immutable, fully tree-shakeable (only imported functions are bundled), has comprehensive TypeScript types, and has a function-per-operation API that works naturally with the ES module system. Luxon and Day.js were also considered; date-fns was chosen over Luxon due to simpler tree-shaking

